    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Afghanistan Aid Is at Roots of Global Terrorism</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Engel Szwaja-Franken letter comments on Aug 16 Robert M Gates Op-Ed article; says same fundamentalists funded by US in crusade against Soviets in Afghanistan during Reagan Administration are now turning to terrorism against US</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Robert M. Gates (Op-Ed, Aug. 16) makes the same assumptions that most of those who write about terrorism do: that it is a phenomenon that sprang from forces outside United States control. However, if the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania were committed by Islamic fundamentalists, our Government played an indirect role in them.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Robert M. Gates (Op-Ed, Aug. 16) makes the same assumptions that most of those who write about terrorism do: that it is a phenomenon that sprang from forces outside United States control. However, if the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania were committed by Islamic fundamentalists, our Government played an indirect role in them.</p>
        <p>In the crusade against the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan, the Reagan Administration financed fundamentalists who happened to be anti-Soviet. After the war, some Muslim recruitees returned to their home countries and found new enemies  in secular Arab governments and their ally, the United States. Thus, these groups might share responsibility for these recent acts of terrorism.</p>
        <p>ENGEL SZWAJA-FRANKEN  Madison, Wis., Aug. 16, 1998</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
